    <h3>2) Clear History Privacy Tool</h3>

    <p>This new tool which is currently on trial in Ireland, Spain and South Korea was devised in the wake of the Cambridge Analytica scandal and gives users enhanced data privacy control for any “off-Facebook” activity. What this means is that users can clear or block any sites or apps that have gathered data on you off-Facebook which could subsequently be used for ad targeting.</p>

    <h2>A bleak future?</h2>

    <p>Whilst providing more transparency and control is a step in the right direction, with firms like Facebook continuing to operate with increased dominion over our everyday lives, it can feel like we are powerlessly walking into an Orwellian future. Although it is difficult to establish definitively whether big tech is listening in and using this data to fuel advertising, what we do know is that user data is becoming an increasingly precious commodity that can have significant consequences, when used either for good or for bad.</p>

    <p>Whilst the obvious answer is to disassociate yourself, whether it be through permanently deleting your account or removing any trace of these apps from your devices, the pervasiveness of such technologies mean that this is becoming an increasingly difficult feat. Digital assistants, Smartphones, Smart Cars and Smart homes all serve to make our lives easier, albeit at the expense of freely offering our personal data. Combine this with the fact that the imposition of any form of government regulation on private tech firms is a morally grey and hotly debated area, it remains to be seen how the future will play out from an ethical data use standpoint.</p>


